  "sections": {
    "Background": {
      "text": "Inflammatory condition involving the apocrine gland-bearing areas of skin, characterized by recurrent painful draining nodules.\n[1]\nMore common in women and black or biracial individuals.\n[2]\nRarely occurs before puberty.  Peak age of onset is 11–20 yo in women and 21–30 yo in men.\n[3]",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": []
    },
    "Clinical_Features": {
      "text": "Tender, nodular lesions most often in the axillae (can also affect gluteal folds, inframammary areas, perianal area, and pubic/genitofemoral areas)\nMalodorous drainage\nPruritis\nBurning\nErythema\nHyperhidrosis\nScarring\n[4]",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": [
        {
          "text": "Pruritis",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Pruritis"
        }
      ]
    },
    "Differential_Diagnosis": {
      "text": "Epidermoid or dermoid cyst\nInflammatory acne\nGranuloma inguinale\nLymphogranuloma venereum",
